<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18771022-763">
               <interp inst="t18771022-763" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18771022"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18771022-763" type="date" value="18771022"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18771022-763-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-763-18771022 t18771022-763-offence-1 t18771022-763-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>763. <persName id="def1-763-18771022" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-763-18771022" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-763-18771022" type="age" value="57"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-763-18771022" type="surname" value="LEACH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-763-18771022" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-763-18771022" type="occupation" value="former landlord"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">HENRY LEACH</hi> (57)</persName>
                  <rs id="t18771022-763-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18771022-763-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="damage"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18771022-763-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="arson"></interp>, Feloniously setting fire to the dwelling-house of <persName id="t18771022-name-125" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-125" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-125" type="surname" value="LINTOTT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-125" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-125" type="occupation" value="packer at Covent Garden Market"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18771022-763-offence-1 t18771022-name-125"></join>Thomas Lintott</persName>, persons being therein.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. FULTON</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution; and</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. AUSTIN METCALFE</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">the Defence.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18771022-name-126" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-126" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-126" type="surname" value="LINTOTT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-126" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS LINTOTT</persName>
                  </hi>. I lodge at 24, Red Lion Street, and am a packer employed at Covent Garden Market—I occupy the front kitchen with my wife and two children—on 3rd October I left home with my wife, my</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187710220029"></xptr>
               <p>children were at school; my wife locked the room, leaving nobody there—she put the key in her pocket—I left her, and went to Covent Garden Market, and about 12.50 she came and told me something—I went home and found the door burst open, and the room in great disorder—the bed was in one place, and the mattress in another, and I could see that there had been a fire; it had been put out—the bed and mattress had been burnt; we had no bedstead—there was very little fire burning when I left, only as much as you could put in your hand, and no gas—the bed was usually rolled up and put in a corner, but on that day it was not rolled up, because we wanted to go out, and it was huddled up in a corner, where a spark could not get to it—when I got back the bed was dis<lb></lb>tributed all over the kitchen, it had been removed out of the corner, and torn to pieces to put the fire out—I also found part of the sheets—the walls are wood, they were not burnt at all, but the floor was burnt close to where the bed was, and under the mantelpiece it was all charred—the prisoner was formerly landlord—I cannot say whether he was then—his sister used to come for the rent—he did not live in the house—I have heard Mm say a great many times that sooner than lose the house through not being able to pay the rent he would burn it, and all the b——people in it—when he gave way to drink he always said so, but not when he was in his sober senses—I went to the fire brigade station, and gave information to the police—the value of my things was 4<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. or 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined.</hi> I heard him threaten so often that I never thought he intended to do it—I believe he rents the house from some person; I do not know who—he told me that he paid 60<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. a year from it, but I do not know what profit he makes, or what the other people pay him—I live rent free for seeing to the house—the bed lies flat on the floor.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18771022-name-127" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-127" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-127" type="surname" value="TURNER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-127" type="given" value="SARAH"></interp>SARAH TURNER</persName>
                  </hi>. I occupy the back kitchen of this house in the base<lb></lb>ment, there are only two rooms down there, mine and Lintott's—on 3rd October I heard the prisoner come down the kitchen stairs—I did not see him, but I heard him speak, and knew his voice—he knocked at Lintott's door <hi rend="italic">two</hi> or three times, and I heard him say "Open the b——door"—I heard him burst it open, and he was in the room a quarter of an hour; he then came out and shut the door very violently, and came upstairs—about five minutes after that a child came down to go into the kitchen, and screamed out "Mrs. Turner, our house is on fire"—I then went into lintott's kitchen and saw the bed on fire, near the fireplace, and the flames were blazing very high—the kitchen is rather dark, but it was a fine day, and a person going there would not require a light—I screamed to Mrs. Clark to bring some water, and ran upstairs and called Mr. Eady—after the flames were got down a little I went to the street door, and saw the prisoner walking up and down outside, while the fire was still burning—I said "You wicked old man, you have set the house alight"—he abused me, and said that I did not pay my way—I did not owe him anything—I then went back, and the fire was pretty well got out—I saw shavings and flock burning on the floor, which were from the mattress and bed—I have heard the prisoner say several times that he would burn the——house down, and all that were in it—he was sometimes drunk and sometimes sober when he said that—I do not know what the occasion was, but I believe he got into difficulties—he was not sober on 3rd October, but he was accountable for his actions—he had been drinking the day before.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187710220030"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined.</hi> He was not walking up and down the pavement when I spoke to him—he was sitting in Mr. Healey's shop while the fire was burning, but Mr. Healey turned him out and locked the door he did not run away.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">By the Court.</hi> There was just a spark in the grate when the bed was burning, you could not say that it was a fire, it was so <hi rend="italic">very</hi> low.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18771022-name-128" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-128" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-128" type="surname" value="CRASK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-128" type="given" value="CATHERINE"></interp>CATHERINE CRASK</persName>
                  </hi>. I am married, and live at 26, Eagle Street—on 3rd October I was working for Mrs. Turner, and heard the prisoner come downstairs—I know him and know his voice—he went to the door several tunes and said "Open the b——door"—he pushed it and went into the room, and we heard him walk across the floor—he stayed in the room a quarter of an hour, and then I heard him go upstairs, and my attention was then called to smoke coming out of the room, and a little girl came and called out, and I took some pails of water and threw over the fire—the bed was all piled up in a heap by the fireplace and blazing—there was a little fire in the grate but very small, not enough to have caused the bed to catch fire—it was a dead fire, merely a <hi rend="italic">few</hi> cinders—the floor was burnt where the bed was, and also part of the fireplace, the wainscoting.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18771022-name-129" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-129" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-129" type="surname" value="HEALEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-129" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN HEALEY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a bootmaker, of 24, Red Lion Street—the prisoner is my landlord—on 3rd October he came into my shop a little before 12 o'clock and stopped there some time until he saw Mr. and Mrs. Lintott go out, and then within a minute he went towards the kitchen, and was absent about a quarter of an hour, and came back and eat down in my shop again, but said nothing till some people passing saw smoke coming from the front kitchen, and I said, "It looks as if the house was on fire, Leach"—he said, "It does"—Lintott's little girl then went through, and came back and halloed out, "Oh, Mr. Leach, the house is on tire"—he said nothing, but sat there till the alarm was given, and then I told him to go out, and I locked my shop door and went down to the kitchen and found the door open and a great smoke and a blaze—I could hardly get in for the smoke, and I told the women to fetch some water—thu mattress and bedding were all piled up against the fireplace, level with the mantelpiece—I soused water over it and turned it over—there was a bundle of wood between the mattress and the floor; not the whole bundle, it was opened and it was burning with the mattress—there was a mass of blaze altogether—the floor was burnt and part of the mantel-piece and the wainscoting—after I put the fixe out I came upstairs and saw Leach standing on the threshold, where some people were accusing him of it, and he said "I mean to burn the b——lot out," and with that he went away—he has been in the habit of drinking on and off all the time I have known him, about eight months—I can't say that he was drunk on this day.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined.</hi> It was a day "off," but he was suffering from the effects of a day "on"—he certainly understood that the house was on fire—he could see it; he knew what he was about—I was quite friendly with him, the best of friends—my workshop is at the top of the place—if the shop had been burnt I should have been burnt out too—he sat in my shop for about five minutes, till the fire was found out—he had not said anything to me about going to search for anything before he went down into the kitchen—he said nothing about going to search for a waistcoat or a purse—he had no candle with him or any wood—I believe the owner</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187710220031"></xptr>
               <p>of the house is a lady in Jersey, according to "what the prisoner has told me he rents the house from her agent, who collects the rents—I believe be pays 60<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. a year, besides rates and taxes—I suppose the house brings in about 150<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18771022-name-130" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-130" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-130" type="surname" value="HOOPER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-130" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN HOOPER</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">Policeman E</hi> 223). On the evening of 3rd October, about 5.30, I took the prisoner into custody—he was perfectly sober—I told him it was for setting fire to a bed at 24, Red Lion Street—he said that he had done it, but accidentally, that he had missed a purse and something else the day before, and he went to look for it, and acci<lb></lb>dentally dropped a match on the bed.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined.</hi> He was searched at the station, nothing was found on him but two or three coppers and an old knife, no matches.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18771022-name-131" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-131" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-131" type="surname" value="LINTOTT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18771022-name-131" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS LINTOTT</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">re-examined</hi>). I was at home the day before—the prisoner did not come to my room that day—I never heard of his having lost a purse—he had not been in my place for six or seven weeks—I had a bundle of wood on the hob in the kitchen to dry—when I went in again it was gone from there and was partly burnt under the bed.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MRS. LINTOTT</hi>. I was at home the day before the fire—the prisoner was not in the kitchen that day, I am quite sure—I did not hear of his having lost a purse.</p>
               <p>
